#compdef syno-photo-frame
# =============================================================================
# syno-photo-frame — Caleb9 (Piotr Karasinski)'s "Build a
#                    digital photo frame for Synology Photos
#                    or Immich with Raspberry Pi" — a Rust
#                    full-screen slideshow CLI for displaying
#                    Synology Photos or Immich shared photo
#                    albums on a Raspberry Pi (or any Linux
#                    system with SDL2).  Fetches photos from
#                    the album, scales them to screen
#                    dimensions, applies crossfade /
#                    fade-to-black transitions, and renders
#                    via SDL2 with optional photo metadata
#                    overlay.
#                    Distinguishing from PixelFrame, DigiFrame,
#                    Daylight (proprietary), and other digital
#                    photo frame solutions by:
#                      - SYNOLOGY PHOTOS + IMMICH BACKENDS —
#                        single binary supports both Synology
#                        Photos (the proprietary NAS photo app)
#                        AND Immich (the self-hosted Google
#                        Photos replacement); --backend auto
#                        detects from URL
#                      - PUBLIC ALBUM ACCESS — requires only a
#                        public shared-album link (no API key,
#                        no auth token for public albums);
#                        password-protected links supported via
#                        -p flag
#                      - SDL2 FULL-SCREEN RENDERING — uses
#                        SDL2 + SDL2_gfx + SDL2_ttf for direct
#                        framebuffer display (works on
#                        Raspberry Pi without X11)
#                      - 5 SLIDESHOW ORDERINGS via -o flag:
#                          * by-date            — older first
#                          * by-date-descending — newer first
#                          * by-name            — alphabetical
#                          * by-name-descending — reverse alpha
#                          * random             — shuffled
#                      - 2 TRANSITION EFFECTS via -t flag:
#                          * crossfade          — cross dissolve
#                          * fade-to-black      — black-then-fade
#                          * none               — instant change
#                      - 2 BACKGROUND FILL EFFECTS — for photos
#                        not matching aspect ratio:
#                          * blur               — blurred photo
#                                                 fills extra space
#                          * none               — black bars
#                      - 4 SCREEN ROTATIONS — 0° / 90° / 180° /
#                        270° via --rotate (for portrait-
#                        oriented displays)
#                      - PHOTO METADATA OVERLAY via
#                        --display-photo-info — show photo
#                        date + GPS location; --datetime-format
#                        controls strftime template
#                      - PHOTO CHANGE INTERVAL via -i SECONDS
#                        (default 30s, minimum 5s)
#                      - SOURCE SIZE HINT via --source-size —
#                        request specific Synology Photos
#                        thumbnail size to reduce bandwidth:
#                          * S (small)   — fastest, lower quality
#                          * M (medium)  — balanced
#                          * L (large)   — full quality (default)
#                      - HTTP TIMEOUT via --timeout SECONDS
#                        (default 30s, minimum 5s); fails with
#                        on-screen error if server doesn't
#                        respond
#                      - REQWEST BLOCKING HTTP — uses reqwest
#                        with blocking + cookies + json + form
#                        + query features (linked from this
#                        completion's primary cross-language
#                        Axis 16 entry R649 _rustormy)
#                      - CHRONO DATETIME — uses chrono with
#                        unstable-locales feature for locale-
#                        aware date formatting (system LC_ALL /
#                        LC_TIME / LANG control format)
#                      - CUSTOM SPLASH SCREEN via --splash
#                        FILE.jpg — replaces default startup
#                        image
#                      - UPDATE CHECK via --disable-update-check
#                        — by default checks GitHub releases
#                        for newer versions during startup
#                    Used by: Raspberry Pi hobbyists building
#                    digital photo frames for family + business
#                    displays, Synology NAS owners
#                    (~3M Synology Photos users globally)
#                    repurposing old smartphones / tablets /
#                    Pi Zero hardware, Immich users
#                    (self-hosted Google Photos alternative)
#                    wanting kiosk-mode display, and as a
#                    reference implementation of image-rs/image
#                    + reqwest + SDL2 + clap derive + chrono
#                    composition in Rust embedded / kiosk
#                    applications.
#
# Author:  Piotr Karasinski (caleb9 on GitHub) — Polish Rust
#          developer.  syno-photo-frame released 2023; active
#          development through 2026; current version 0.17.0.
#          License: GPL-3.0-or-later.
# Source:  https://github.com/caleb9/syno-photo-frame
#          https://github.com/caleb9/syno-photo-frame/blob/main/src/cli.rs
#          https://github.com/caleb9/syno-photo-frame/blob/main/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     src/cli.rs — uses clap v4 derive (well-documented
#          elsewhere).  Headline library: **image** (the new
#          variant being documented here, opening Axis 22 —
#          Image Processing).
# Library: image (https://github.com/image-rs/image —
#          "Encoding and decoding images in Rust" — image-rs
#          working group, originally PistonDevelopers/image;
#          now maintained by the image-rs GitHub organization.
#          Distinct from all previously-documented Rust
#          libraries by being:
#             1. CROSS-FORMAT IMAGE I/O — image decodes +
#                encodes 14+ formats with a unified API:
#                  * JPEG    (read + write; via image-jpeg)
#                  * PNG     (read + write; via png-rs)
#                  * GIF     (read + write; via gif-rs)
#                  * WEBP    (read; via webp-rs)
#                  * AVIF    (read; via libavif-rs)
#                  * BMP     (read + write)
#                  * TIFF    (read + write; via tiff-rs)
#                  * TGA     (read + write)
#                  * PNM     (read + write — PPM/PGM/PBM)
#                  * DDS     (read; DirectDraw Surface)
#                  * ICO     (read + write)
#                  * HDR     (read + write — Radiance HDR)
#                  * EXR     (read + write — OpenEXR)
#                  * Farbfeld(read + write)
#                  * QOI     (read + write — Quite OK Image)
#                  * OpenEXR (read + write)
#                Distinct from format-specific Rust libraries
#                (png-rs, jpeg-decoder, libavif-rs); image
#                provides ONE API across all formats.
#             2. DynamicImage + ImageBuffer DUAL API —
#                ImageBuffer<P: Pixel, Vec<P::Subpixel>> for
#                typed-at-compile-time pixel access;
#                DynamicImage enum for runtime-polymorphic
#                handling of various color types (Rgb8, Rgba8,
#                Luma8, Rgb16, Rgba32F, etc.):
#                  use image::{ImageReader, DynamicImage};
#                  let img: DynamicImage = ImageReader::open("photo.jpg")?.decode()?;
#                  let img = img.resize(800, 600, image::imageops::FilterType::Lanczos3);
#                  let img = img.brighten(20);
#                  let img = img.adjust_contrast(15.0);
#                  img.save("output.jpg")?;
#             3. IMAGE PROCESSING via image::imageops — built-
#                in operations: resize (4 filter types:
#                Nearest, Triangle, CatmullRom, Lanczos3),
#                rotate (90/180/270), flip horizontal +
#                vertical, brighten, adjust_contrast, blur
#                (Gaussian), unsharpen, crop, overlay,
#                replace, vertical_gradient, horizontal_gradient.
#             4. NO-STD COMPATIBLE — image's core
#                ImageBuffer/Pixel/Subpixel types work in
#                no_std contexts (embedded);
#                format-specific encoders/decoders are
#                feature-gated and require std.
#             5. PIXEL TRAIT GENERICITY — image is generic over
#                pixel types (Pixel trait):
#                  pub trait Pixel: Copy + Clone {
#                      type Subpixel: Primitive;
#                      const CHANNEL_COUNT: u8;
#                      // ...
#                  }
#                Built-in pixel types: Rgb<T>, Rgba<T>,
#                Luma<T>, LumaA<T> with T = u8, u16, f32.
#                Custom pixel types implementable for HDR,
#                multispectral, etc.
#             6. ITERATOR-BASED PIXEL ACCESS — `for (x, y,
#                pixel) in img.enumerate_pixels()` for
#                row-major iteration; `for (x, y, pixel) in
#                img.enumerate_pixels_mut()` for in-place
#                modification.
#             7. FORMAT-FEATURE GATING — each format is a Cargo
#                feature; build with only formats you need to
#                minimize binary size:
#                  image = { version = "0.25", default-features
#                            = false, features = ["jpeg", "png"] }
#                syno-photo-frame uses this (only jpeg + png
#                for photo frame use case).
#             8. PARALLEL DECODE via rayon — opt-in parallel
#                JPEG/PNG decoding via "rayon" Cargo feature;
#                useful for batch processing.
#             9. PISTON-DEVELOPERS / image-rs ECOSYSTEM
#                PROVENANCE — image originated in
#                PistonDevelopers (Rust game-engine project)
#                circa 2014; now maintained by image-rs
#                working group with contributors HeroicKatora,
#                Nemo157, fintelia, gleason-m, etc.
#                Distinct from format-specific maintainers
#                (Bastian Köcher / png-rs, vihotcat / jpeg-
#                decoder, image-rs / gif-rs, etc.) — image
#                aggregates these.
#            10. RUST WORKING GROUP MAINTAINED — image-rs is a
#                Rust working group (small team of trusted
#                maintainers), not a single-author project.
#                Distinct from David Tolnay (serde) and Sean
#                McArthur (Hyperium) which are individual-
#                maintainer.  Working-group structure ensures
#                continuity across maintainer turnover.)
